<paper id="1788335386"><title>A One Way Function Based on Ideal Arithmetic in Number Fields</title><year>1997</year><authors><author org="TH Darmstadt" id="1552168940">Johannes Buchmann</author><author org="TH Darmstadt" id="2706276063">Sachar Paulus</author></authors><n_citation>17</n_citation><doc_type>Conference</doc_type><references><reference>1490994218</reference><reference>1496801598</reference><reference>1519023517</reference><reference>1570514484</reference><reference>1583363970</reference><reference>1989510734</reference><reference>1990820504</reference><reference>1996360405</reference><reference>2026129593</reference></references><venue id="1153524033" type="C">International Cryptology Conference</venue><doi>10.1007/BFb0052250</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.46924">Discrete mathematics</keyword><keyword weight="0.54314">Algebraic number</keyword><keyword weight="0.54458">Exponential function</keyword><keyword weight="0.46508">Algebra</keyword><keyword weight="0.53767">Multiplication</keyword><keyword weight="0.57491">Algebraic number field</keyword><keyword weight="0.56476">One-way function</keyword><keyword weight="0.53388">Time complexity</keyword><keyword weight="0.59449">Exponentiation</keyword><keyword weight="0.52616">Number theory</keyword><keyword weight="0.42748">Mathematics</keyword></keywords><publisher>Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg</publisher><abstract>We present a new one way function based on the difficulty of finding shortest vectors in lattices. This new function consists of exponentiation of an ideal in an order of a number field and multiplication by an algebraic number which can both be performed in polynomial time. The best known algorithm for inverting this function is exponential in the degree of the lattices involved.</abstract></paper>